Medical Direction ▸
Patient Advice (Legal Language) ▸

This form is being completed because I have refused medical care and/or treatment as noted above. I understand that ambulance personnel are not physicians and are not qualified or authorized to make a diagnosis of my condition, and that their care is not a substitute for that of a physician. I recognize that I may have a serious injury or illness, which could get worse without medical attention even though I may feel fine at this time. I understand that I may change my mind and call 911 if I decide to accept treatment or need assistance later. I also understand that I may seek treatment from a physician or at an emergency department 24 hours a day. I acknowledge that the ambulance crew has explained this advice to me and that I have read this form completely and understand its provisions. I agree to release, indemnify, and hold harmless the ambulance service and its officers, members, or other agents from any and all claims, actions, cause of action, damages, or legal liabilities of any kind arising out of my condition or the refusal of medical care and/or transport, or of any act or omission of the ambulance service or its crew, even for negligence.

EMT Quick References ▶
BE-FAST Stroke Scale ▶
BBalance — Sudden loss of balance or coordination
EEyes — Sudden vision change or double vision
FFace — Ask to smile; one side drooping?
AArms — Ask to raise both arms; one drifts down?
SSpeech — Slurred, strange, or unable to speak?
TTime — Note onset time. Call immediately.
Last known well time is critical for tPA eligibility window (typically 3–4.5 hrs).
Cincinnati Stroke Scale ▶
1Facial Droop — Ask to show teeth or smile. Normal: both sides move equally. Abnormal: one side doesn't move.
2Arm Drift — Eyes closed, both arms out 10 sec. Normal: equal. Abnormal: one drifts down or pronates.
3Abnormal Speech — "You can't teach an old dog new tricks." Normal: correct words, clear. Abnormal: slurred, wrong words, or none.
1 abnormal finding = 72% probability of stroke. All 3 abnormal = >85%.

Max 15 (normal). ≤8 = severe TBI, consider airway. 9–12 = moderate. 13–15 = mild.
AVPU Scale ▶
AAlert — Awake, aware, responds appropriately
VVoice — Responds only to verbal stimuli
PPain — Responds only to painful stimuli
UUnresponsive — No response to any stimuli
V, P, or U roughly corresponds to GCS ≤13, ≤8, and ≤6 respectively.
OPQRST — Pain Assessment ▶
OOnset — When did it start? What were you doing?
PProvocation/Palliation — What makes it better or worse?
QQuality — Sharp, dull, crushing, burning, tearing?
RRadiation — Does it go anywhere else? Jaw, arm, back?
SSeverity — Rate 0–10. How does it compare to prior episodes?
TTime — Constant or intermittent? Getting better or worse?
SAMPLE History ▶
SSigns & Symptoms — Chief complaint, what patient notices
AAllergies — Medications, environmental, food
MMedications — Rx, OTC, herbals, patches, inhalers
PPertinent History — Relevant past medical/surgical history
LLast Oral Intake — Food and drink, when
EEvents — What led up to this? Any trauma or triggers?

SpO₂ & BGL Reference ▶
SpO₂ ≥95% Normal
91–94% Mild hypoxia — supplemental O₂
86–90% Moderate — high-flow O₂
≤85% Severe — immediate intervention
BGL 70–110 mg/dL Normal (fasting)
<70 mg/dL Hypoglycemia — treat
>180 mg/dL Hyperglycemia
>300 mg/dL Critical — monitor closely

Palm of patient's hand ≈ 1% BSA. Burns >20% BSA, airway, or circumferential = critical.
Shock — Signs & Types ▶
Compensated vs. Decompensated
CompensatedNormal BP, ↑HR, pale/cool/diaphoretic, anxiety, ↑RR
Decompensated↓BP, altered LOC, mottling — imminent arrest
Types
HypovolemicHemorrhage, dehydration, burns
CardiogenicMI, CHF, arrhythmia — JVD, crackles
DistributiveSeptic, anaphylactic, neurogenic
ObstructiveTension PTX, tamponade, PE
